column1: What do you call it when an inmate takes a picture of their-self? a cellfie
column3: In the context of the joke, cell refers to both a prison cell and a small unit of biological life (cell).
column4: The prisoner spent his days locked in a small cell, counting the days until his release.
column5: Under a microscope, the scientist observed the structure and function of the cell.

column1: Whats the difference between a snow-man and a snow-woman? snowballs
column3: Here, balls refers to both the physical snowballs that are used to make a snowman and a colloquial term for testicles.
column4: The children laughed as they threw snowballs at each other during the winter storm.
column5: During the annual health check, the doctor discussed the importance of mens health concerning their balls.

column1: What did the father buffalo say to his son going off to college? bison
column3: In the joke, bison contains a play on words where the word refers to both the animal and the goodbyes offered to a son as he leaves for college.
column4: The bison roamed freely across the plains, a majestic sight under the blue sky.
column5: The fathers bison was filled with pride as he sent his son off to pursue higher education.
